VARIABLES: 
In Java, variables are like your personal storage boxes that hold data. 📦
Your boxes can be given names that hold and store a value (numbers, letters, emojis, etc).

int points = 22;
System.out.println(points); // Output: 22
ou can then reference the variable name to access the value stored inside. In our print statement, points is the variable name, and 22 is the value stored inside.

In this example:

int is the type (the variable will hold an integer).
points is the variable name.
= is the assignment symbol.
# Naming
A common naming convention in Java is camelCase, in which the first word is written in all lowercase letters, and the following words start with an uppercase letter.

int groupOfStudents = 20;
int numberOfStudents = 10;

Variable names typically start with a letter. You can use these names to access your data later in your program! 👏🏻
Additionally, variable names must follow a few rules:

They are case-sensitive (Age and age are different variables).
They cannot contain whitespaces or special characters like !, #, %, etc.
They must begin with a letter; it can't start with a number.

